segments.text: See ya!
This is an interview.
My name is Isabel Fernandez, and today's date is the 17th of November of 1984.
I'm going to interview Francisco Jose Guerrero from El Salvador, son of Francisco Jose Guerrero, leader of National Conciliation Party, PCN.
Today we're going to discuss US influence on El Salvador elections of 1984.
Now, tell me something about your father.
Well, he, in 1961, when there was military power in El Salvador, there were a few military people and conservative people get together and formed the PCN, which was a rough copy of the PRI.
from Mexico.
Then, you know, they had a Congress election, and PCN took all the seats in the Congress.
And my father got elected president of the Congress.
That was 1962.
But the president was, who was it, Molina?
No, it was Rivera, Coronel Rivera.
Then in 67, it was General...
General Fidel Sanchez Hernandez got elected president from the PCN party, and my father was elected minister of foreign affairs.
Oh, okay.
In 71, the military took the whole control of the PCN party.
which, you know, my father didn't like at all, because, you know, it was a mix-up between conservative people and military people.
So he resigned.
From the PCN.
From the PCN.
That was 71.
And he got out of the politics until 80...
It was 80.
The PCN party got thrown out of power by some military...
It was October 15, 1979.
And they were hassled.
They were threatened.
They couldn't have meeting together because the military junta was to kill that party.
They decided that they didn't want no PCN to exist.
Then my father and some other conservative people started rebuilding the party for the 82 election.
But there was another party formed from the PCN, which was ARENA.
In 72, there was Coronel Molina, the president.
And in 77, it was Coronel Romero, the president.
Both of those people that formed the government, that the PCN took from 72 to 79, those were the people who formed ARENA.
Which, you know, it was more, they were more conservative.
than the PCN really was.
So it was more right.
That's what they call the ultra-right.
And in 81, my father, he decided to start rebuilding the PCN, as I was saying.
And then in 82, we won 14 congressmen out of 60.
The Democratic Party
got 24 and Arena got 19.
Okay.
Then my father got elected prime minister for that because, you know, they divided.
It was a Congress election in 82.
So they all got together to form a coalition government, all the parties.
And my father got elected prime minister.
In 81.
In 82.
Then he resigned in 82.
And by the end of 83, he resigned because he was going to run for president for the PCN party.
And today he's... Today, you know, he got elected president of the Supreme Court, which is an election.
He doesn't form, he doesn't, he's a part for the Duarte's government.
Because he's elected from the Congress, which Duarte doesn't have the majority.
So, you know, he's like the head of the opposition in El Salvador.
Okay.
And you were helping your father with the campaign of 1980?
Yeah, that's why I left from here.
Because he needed help, you know, like, to trust, to have a lot of trust, and talking to...
trying to get, you know, whatever help we could because, you know, they didn't think that the PCN could be rebuilt.
Oh, I see.
So you were talking to the people?
Yeah, I was talking to the people, trying to get the T-shirts, cheaper T-shirts.
You know, we got about 200,000 plates, you know, with the PCN symbol.
That's, you know, for the peasants, you know, some of them.
All right.
Okay, I'm going to ask you the first question.
What sector of the population supported your father, Spartan?
Easy.
Let me explain this.
Okay.
Okay, now Salvador, we got most of the peasants.
Of the peasants?
But since, you know, these people, these people who used to own the big lands...
they formed the other party, which was ARENA.
Those were the rich people, right?
Yeah, the rich people.
And they tried to convince the peasants to vote for ARENA, not for PCN.
And it got up to a point, you know, where we were really close.
Arena and PCN.
What about Duarte?
Well, he was always, you know, in the head.
Yeah, he was always ahead.
So he was first, and then your father's party and Arena were second.
Yeah, but, you know, we never got together on the second thing because all they want is... PCN was always the ultra-right party in El Salvador.
And my father, he worked so hard to make it look, you know, to make it, to put it, put the party in the middle and, you know, leave it right now to the ultra right.
All right.
So he wanted to be more center.
So, you know, he told all his followers that, you know, they could vote, you know, for whoever they want.
But there is always, before, there were always two parties, PCN and PDC.
And, you know, they're,
Most of the followers were going to vote against PDC, which is Duarte's party.
Yes, because they've been voting like that all their lives.
I see.
So the population that supported your father was the peasants, right?
Most of the peasants and a few rich people, very few.
So can it be said that your father's party was the military's party?
No, no way.
It was the old military party.
The old ones.
Yeah, the old ones.
Like, you know, most of them, you know, are out of office.
You know, they are generals, but, you know, out of office.
So what party did the military support, like?
Oh, you know, they... Maybe.
You know, some of them went for us, some of them went for ARENA, most of them went for ARENA.
Oh, so most of the military were... Yeah, because in El Salvador, since there is a war going on, there is a lot of young military people.
And they are more into bullets than dialogue.
I see.
And my father was always for the dialogue.
Okay.
But, you know, we got help, Duarte got help from the military too.
Oh, you know, the mayor took part in ghetto.
Okay.
Do you see any possibility of the El Salvadorian army taking over the elections since it happened in 1972?
I don't know what happened in 72, but I don't think the army got control of that.
That's what Duarte says.
Yeah, that's what Duarte says, that he won the election.
He really won the election, but he didn't have the majority.
It was a mistake.
I'm glad my father was out of PCN by then, because he won the election for sure, but he didn't have the majority.
So how come he can win the election?
No, because you don't need 50% plus one vote.
You need 51%.
I see.
So that 1% might be 1,000 votes, 10,000 votes, whatever.
And then that was, for me, that was the mistake.
They could have at least give Duarte the benefit of the doubt that he won.
And then, you know, going to Congress, which PCN had the majority, Coronel Molina was going to be elected anyway.
As president?
As president, because, you know, that's the law in El Salvador.
If you don't get the majority, you have to go to Congress.
Oh, and Congress decides.
Decides who wins.
So in this election, the Congress decides for Molina?
Yeah, it was on the military people.
Oh, okay.
All right.
Did the U.S. aid workers help your father with the campaign?
No.
We kind of were told that we were the favorites for the American because Duarte went too far to the left and Daweson went too far to the right.
As you know, we got him talking to Ambassador Pickering a few times.
He said that he'll look at good eyes if my father goes to the second round.
But that's about it.
No, they help us, you know, and getting reporters and getting, you know, a bunch of reporters and media to my father's rabbit.
Did the U.S. aid workers help Duarte's campaign?
The U.S. government didn't help Duarte.
The AFL-CIO gave some money to the AFL-CIO corresponding to El Salvador.
And, you know, they are the new population of El Salvador.
It's like the agrarian reform, people who live in the parts where the agrarian reform were settled.
And, you know, since most of them are peasants, you know, they go door by door, door by door trying to convince people to vote for Duarte because Duarte doesn't have a peasant support.
He didn't?
He didn't have none.
I mean, he won only in three departments out of 14, which were, you know, where the big cities were.
So he won elections in the city?
Yeah, he won the election in the city, but the peasants, you know, always go against him because, you know.
All right.
Okay, it's been said that if the U.S. retires its help from El Salvador, the Salvadorian army will collapse.
Now, it was clear that Reagan administration wanted Duarte to win.
I mean, reading the newspaper, I always read that they wanted Duarte, not your father.
Either Davison didn't want that one at all.
So do you feel that these two facts put a lot of pressure on the election?
People voting for Duarte because maybe they felt that if Davison won...
You know, if you see the figures, the figures are very close.
I think they were 50% to 48%, something like that.
And you can see that most of the peasants vote against Duarte.
They don't vote for Davison.
They vote against Duarte.
Yeah, but your father got 19%.
Davison got 30%.
Davison, okay.
29% and Duarte got like 44%.
43%, right.
So...
I mean, a lot of people support him.
He kept that vote.
He kept, you know, the people that vote for him, you know, they vote again.
People from Arena and PCN, they're more used to, since, you know, we were the official party for so many years.
the peasants from the PCN were more used to having buses to take them to the boating places.
And this time, since we were not an official party, neither Arena was, we couldn't put no buses.
Oh, I see.
So you see, most of the people who vote, they just vote.
No, but if you compare the results from the first round and the second round, you'll see that Duarte kept their votes.
He didn't win, you know, people from the PCN or people from other parties.
But Arena, he won most of the PCN.
But they didn't vote for Dawison because, you know, it was Dawison.
They voted against Duarte.
All right.
So you're saying that the people didn't vote for Duarte?
No.
Okay, I see.
During the campaign, did you get any threats from any side?
We got threats from all sides.
You see, since, you know, we were the middle, which Duarte's party used to be the middle party.
All right.
But the guerrillas used to be the far left.
But this time, you know, we were in the middle.
We got threatened by...
leftists, by guerrillas, by right.
Really?

Yeah, we get, you know, there was once, you know, when I had to tell, you know, I had to really stand, you know, and tell them, man, if you're going to use that, if you're going to pull that gun, you better use it.
Because, you know, there was this major of this city from Arena, that he just went to the rally.
and says, you know, there is no rally in here.
And I was the only one presenting my father's party in there and a group that was playing music.
Because, you know, we were the ones that had the always very happy rallies, you know, music, pupusas, and everything.
Because, you know, we wanted to feel happy.
Most of our buddies are young people.
All right.
And, you know, this guy just went, you know, and told us he's the boss from that town, and I told him.
So he didn't let you speak to the people?
We didn't.
Oh, okay.
Because we have security, too.
All right.
In your opinion, why didn't the guerrillas show up their ballot to the elections?
Because they don't have the support of the people.
If they're
They're burning buses.
They're burning things that the majority of the people use.
I got my own car.
If they burn a bus in El Salvador, I'm not using that bus.
The majority of the people are using it.
The bridges, they explode.
You see, I can take a plane and fly over.
But the passengers, they cannot afford it.
the majority of the support of the people they don't like for it.
So you think that it's because they knew that the people wouldn't vote for them, so they decided not to show up?
I see.
Did you feel that the elections were a farce made in USA so that Reagan could call Congress and keep on sending military help?
No, it wasn't.
It wasn't.
You see, he won.
He won mainly
Because it was about time.
He's been trying for so long to be a president.
He was the president of the Junta, which is not elected.
I'm sure that if all the parties get together, all the opposition parties, we can beat Duarte.
But we never did that.
That was our promise, to let Duarte go.
All right.
Was the people forced to vote by threats from the different parties?
And did they vote just out of fear?
No, not really.
You see, the people went to vote.
They wanted to vote?
They wanted to vote.
They wanted to elect somebody.
So, okay.
You know, there were no force, no matter.
Okay, after the first election, Duarte and his son were tied, right?
And a runoff was necessary.
Did your father get any kind of financial help from CIA so that he couldn't help Duarte, he would help Duarte?
We couldn't, we didn't, you see, the main problem of my father's campaign was money-wise.
Right.
Because, you know, he...
He paid out of his own package most of the campaign.
If we could have at least $436,000, I think that's what they said, that my father received, and that campaign, I'm sure we would end up in second place.
No, but I mean afterwards.
Afterwards.
So that your father wouldn't... No.
We got together with the arena party to talk.
And they just went, clearly, we got a cake.
Let's divide it.
Everyone can do whatever they want, but let's divide it half and half.
And my father is not like that.
See, he's been in the politics for so long that he told me, I want these issues.
to be corrected from your party, you know, I'll give you all.
Even they wanted to change that was on for my father.
I mean, my father for that was on.
And there was a law given around those days that my father was going to be able to run for arena.
And he didn't accept.
Oh, really?
Yeah, he just went straight and told them, too much talking, and no, no, we're not doing nothing.
I see.
But if you compare figures, most of our people, we have a neutrality.
But at the same time, we're against Duarte's party.
See, most of our people vote for Arena.
Okay.
Davison wanted a military victory over the guerrillas.
So did your father, right?
No, my father was for the dialogue all the time.
He was?
Yeah.
So that's the reason for which your father didn't help Davison on the run-up?
No, it wasn't just because of that, because it was going to be
decided between two polarizations.
If that was on one, it was bad for our country.
We could win a prison, but the country wouldn't be getting arms, bullets, which are needed now.
So that's, you didn't, your father, okay.
No, but you know, he went ahead and told me, you know, I'm neutral, but I like that we sound better.
So if the U.S. had been kept out of this election, would your father have joined Aluson?
No, I don't think so.
Like if the U.S. didn't have anything to do?
You know, there was one point where, you know, the support from both parties was almost real.
Almost real.
But, you know, there were people in the arena that they just wanted to have the power to give their farms back.

give their banks back you know there were things it was like you know going back give their banks back to rich people so that's what that's what my father told me my father told me there is no way this can be done so that's the reason why your father didn't join the he didn't join it publicly underground I was offered
to go on a commercial with the arena.
But you just, okay, wait a minute, wait a minute.
You just told me that you didn't, your father didn't join Davison publicly because you knew that if Davison had won the election, you wouldn't receive any more help.
Issues, also the issues.
Okay, that's the other thing, okay.
Like, you know, like you say, he wanted a military victory.
We wanted dialogue.
He was, you know, to, my father was for, to get the, all the, all the reformers to make them good.
Dawesan wanted to take them all out.
So it sounds to me that your father was more, ideologically, he was more close to Duarte than to Dawesan.
And the issues.
Right, and the issues.
And the issues.
But Duarte is not, you know, what you're hearing here.
He's not?
He's not, because, you know, I was with him at, you know, we met with both parties.
But usually with the PDC, with Duarte's party, we just had an hour or something like that.
But with that we saw, you see, we always ended up, you know, until next day.
Ah, I see.
You know, here I read, like, I thought it was, I think Newsweek, somewhere like that, said that your father was helping Duarte.
He was getting together with Duarte.
Yeah, he was getting together with Duarte.
Yes, he did.
So publicly, he was helping Duarte?
No, publicly, no.
You know, first thing, after the first round,
He said, exactly, I won't go anywhere.
Whoever wants me, you know, go to my house.
Duarte, being the first, the first, the first place, you know, in the first round, the election was Sunday, and he was in my house Monday at 8 o'clock in the morning.
Yeah, because your father's party was the decisive party.
Yeah, yeah.
It was up to your father who was going to win.
It was up to my father who was going to win.
But it's not true that either.
So your father didn't help any party?
Well, he helped on the other table more than Davison.
He helped Davison?
But still Davison lost?
But still Davison lost because he didn't win out publicly.
Oh, all right.
Okay, do you think that in case of a Davison victory, the U.S. will have taken military action?
The military action against what?
Against your country.
I mean, taking like...
They haven't done it in Nicaragua.
So you don't think it will happen?
Besides, you know, like Duarte says, now, you know, you can hear Duarte, you know, he's more, he's thinking more than talking.
He says, you know, Salvadorian problem belongs to Salvadorian.
That's ideally, actually, but I don't think that's the case.
That's not the case because, you know, we're in a war.
We depend on the states.
But, you know, for like the dialogue that happened about three weeks ago, they didn't invite no American.
So do you think that Davison didn't win the elections because you are in a war and you depend on the U.S.?
Most of the people also, you see, Davison wanted a military victory.
That's because, you know, he lives in the city.
Most of the peasants live in guerrilla-controlled areas where the government troops always go and bomb.
They want peace.
They are tired of military.
War and action, I see.
Okay, will the U.S. cut financial aid if Abuson will have one?
That's been told.
I'm sure they could do that.
It's up to them.
We don't control the United States.
They could have caught it if Duarte had won, too.
Yeah.
Well, the U.S., I mean, the Reagan administration was for Duarte.
That's not true.
Do you think not?
Well, in the newspaper, that's what I got.
Yeah, but that's what they said.
AFL-CIO is the main base for the Democratic Party, not the Republican Party.
And the United States helped Duarte
Through the AFL-CIO.
That's not Duarte's government.
That's not Reagan's government.
But Reagan's the one that's asking Congress.
For help for the country.
Whoever had won it.
But still, if that was some...
It would be harder to get.
It would be harder to get.
It would have been almost impossible to get money from Congress.
That's something that, you know, Guatemala doesn't receive nothing from the states.
Who?
Guatemala.
Oh, Guatemala.
And there, you know, they kill all the guerrillas.
They have more military presence than El Salvador, and they, you know, they just keep them going.
Okay.
What about if Duarte hadn't win the election?
Do you think, okay, it was said that he had planned a popular insurrection in case of a Donald Trump victory.
It's more like a psychological war going on, you know.
They were saying, we got together with Duarte.
That was saying that.
Because my father knew that he didn't like to go with Duarte.
And Duarte was saying, my father was going to that with some.
It was just a psychological war.
The war was nothing else.
Duarte did it in 72.
He got a popular insurrection, but he didn't work.
popular insurrection and there was only a couple thousand people insurrected.
So even if he had had an insurrection he wouldn't have done anything.
Okay.
Do you think that the problems in your country have to be settled down by bullets rather than by ballots?
It all depends because you know they the gorillas depend on Nicaragua and
They don't want to go to election.
They want power.
They don't want to die alone.
If you see on the dialogue, their main, their main, uh, military boss, Joaquin Villalobos, he wasn't in there.
Villalobos.
Because, you know, he wanted, uh, uh, uh, helicopter, a helicopter, you know, flew him from wherever he was to the La Palma.
And even Duarte, who is the president of El Salvador, he dropped.
Because my father went with him.
I see.
So you think that...
They don't really, you know, it has to be settled by ballots because they're going to understand, the guerrillas will understand that they don't have the popular support.
Okay.
Do you feel that no matter who the president is, the Salvadorian army is actually in control, and finally the U.S. is the one deciding for your country?
That's not true either, because what is happening in El Salvador is that there is a war going on.
have to be controlled by military people.
Duarte is the head commandant of all the forces in Los Alamos, but he doesn't understand the war techniques.
I see.
So the military, they take care of the war, and Duarte takes care of the government.
Yeah, okay.
I read somewhere that the armed force lives with Duarte as long as he doesn't attempt to negotiate with the guerrillas
or interfere in any significant way with the army's conduct on the war.
And still, Duarte wants to have dialogue with the guerrillas.
So how can he have dialogue if the army doesn't want him to do anything with the guerrillas?
That's not true.
You see, the dialogue, that was a few phrases, pretty nice.
They're pals.
They're old pals, Duarte and the guerrillas.
It's going to be a monologue.
And that's not true.
Duarte and Ungo, they run for president.
Ungo, right.
They work together.
He runs for president.
But that doesn't mean they have the same ideology.
But they have one thing in common.
They want peace.
But the army doesn't want peace.
The army doesn't want to die alone.
The army wants peace.
They want military victory, right?
you can say that they already have the military victory.
Because the guerrillas in Nicaragua, they fought a couple years, and then Somoza, Somoza government were thrown out in a couple years.
They've been fighting for five years in my country.
They haven't obtained no military victory.
They control certain parts of the country.
But the peasants from there, they moved to Honduras, they moved to
to places where they keep all these people, because they don't support the gorillas.
So the army wants a military victory?
They want some, but they already have the military victory.
So how come you have war?
Because if Nicaragua is in between,
I saw some prisoners of war that didn't even talk Spanish.
They were Russians?
I don't know.
They were black.
From where?
Nobody knows.
They were just bodies.
So it's more like an exterior support war against Osagodoro and Corbin.
which the military doesn't like them to intervene.
That's why they want a military victory, not to kill all the Salvatoreans fighting.
They don't want no Nicaraguan going in there.
Duarte wanted to have land reforms, nationalize the banks and all this.
He already did it.
Right.
Has the election changed the situation at all?
No, not at all.
As a matter of fact, Arena's phrase for this next campaign
They call it the hundred days of nothing.
And that's true because, you know, there is so many things to do that it's impossible to start having results so fast.
The land reform, you know, it was given.
It couldn't have taken out.
So he didn't offer it.
You know, it was already there.
Oh, it was already there.
So but still Duarte cannot do too much because his hands are tied by the military also.
No because you know as I'm saying the military people they're more concerned of the war matter and Duarte is more concerned about laws about you know.
Yeah but if you in a country if you have a war
the most important things, the war, right?
The other things are like, how can you lose if there is a war?
Who's going to respect that?
That's what I mean.
How could Duarte?
You know, he tries, you know, and he tries hard.
So it doesn't matter if you have a president.
I mean, it doesn't make any difference.
That's what you're saying.
Because, you know, the military, you know, they're there to preserve the country.
All right.
And you see, they are taught that way.
They are used to receive orders, and that's the way it should be.
A war is a war.
Okay, so you think you shouldn't have a president then?
Why not?
As far as you have a war, there's no need for a president.
Even in Vietnam, when Johnson was in Vietnam, I'm sure he didn't have no...
No, he had an ideological force sending people over there.
But from over there, the general commander of the forces, he was in charge.
So since the war is in your country, in your own country, then the one that's in charge is the army, right?
Yeah, but Duarte, he has a lot of power, governmental power.
Okay.
Do you think
What do you think about U.S. intervention on the politics of your country?
Do you think they should be more involved or less involved?
Less.
You know, they're okay.
You know, as long as they don't give you orders to do what you do, it's okay.
Because, like, on the dialogue, Ambassador Picker, he said, you know, I'm not invited to that.
It's hard to believe that I'm not invited.
And Duarte answered, you know,
Salvadorian people had to resolve their problems.
Alright.
What about financial help?
We needed it because you know we were the most progressive country in Latin America in 77 and 78 in Latin America, Venezuela, Colombia.
Because you know the Salvadorian people love to work.
They are hard working people.
Okay.
So you think that the involvement of the U.S. is all right?
It's financial and military because, you know, we cannot win a war if we have a machine gun but no bullets.
Do you think they should send more military help to Salvador?
Yeah.
Yes?
So they should get more involved financially but not...
Financially and military because we're...
But not deciding.
Not deciding.
Yes, you know, whatever the government asks them for.
Okay.
All right.
Okay, tell me, what do you think that are the causes of the revolution in your country?
Are they social problems or Marxism?
You know, it started as a...
Okay, social problems, right.
It started like, you know, they were asking for social reforms.
So social problems.
Yeah, but you see...
In El Salvador, there were people with a lot of lands, a lot of farms.
But these people who had the biggest land, you know, they treated their peasants in those lands nicer than anybody else.
Like, you know, I know La Carrera, which was the biggest one.
He had TVs, radio.
He had, I think in
eight or nine schools, he had a hospital, which, you know, the one who owns the land, the owner of the land, he built them for the peasants.
So they'll be happy.
Right now, they don't have electricity, they don't have TVs, they have schools, but, you know, they don't have no teachers.
The hospital doesn't have any medicines.
That's because the people who get control of that farm after the agrarian reform
They didn't know.
They didn't have any buying power.
Which, you know, if one guy owns this, you know, they have buying power.
Okay, so it started out like social problems.
But then, you know, it got controlled by Marxists.
But now it's controlled by Marxists.
So you think that... Because, you know, the peasants, they noticed that the leaders of the revolution were pure blah, blah, blah.
I see.
You know, they just wanted, you know, Marxism.
Because you can see Ungo, he's always traveling in first class.
Really.
Okay.
Ungo Samayo, which was a professor of mine, you know, he always traveled in first class.
When he came to A&M, you know, I took his tie and said, Peter Cardan, man, looks nice on you.
Because, you know, if they are Marxists, you know,
They should dress like that.
They shouldn't be wearing no...
Okay, who do you think supports the guerrillas?
Nicaragua mainly, Cuba.
So you're saying that no Salvadorian peasants are supporting the guerrillas?
Well, not all of them.
But the majority?
The majority is what I'm saying.
